results.notes:
Growing on soil in clay slick spot habitat.

Macro: thallus upper surface light brown to yellow brown, areolate to subsquamulose. Lower surface where present appears off-white in color. Areoles/squamules generally with multiple apothecia, often crowded together. Apothecia lecideine and elevated, with a thick, raised dark rim ~0.1 mm wide. Apothecia up to ~0.8 mm diameter, squamules up to 3mm diam.

Micro: Hymenium ~90 micrometers tall, hemiamyloid (I+reddish). Paraphyses with expanded apical cell up to ~5 micrometers wide, bases of paraphyses 2-3 micrometers wide. Subhymenium/hypothecium I+ blue, ~30 micrometers thick. Outer exciple dark brown to black, becoming hyaline in interior. Exciple expanded to ~50 micrometers. Cells of outer exciple becoming oval. Cortex overlain by epinecral layer, which measured ~50 micrometers thick. Cortex boundary between epinecral layer indistinct, but appears to be ~40 micrometers thick with an upper light brown layer overlaying a hyaline layer. Cortex anatomy indistinct. Asci K/I – (no blue cap). Algal layer even.

Spores: average (n=10): 6.3×3.2 micrometers, >100spores/ascus

Chemistry: thallus C- and K- in section

A single fruiting body growing on a sun-exposed lawn under Norway spruces. The basidiome appeared to be immature but already withering due to the dry and cool weather and, possibly, exposure to the afternoon sun. This spot has previously yielded other amanitas (A. strips Citrina, A. crenulata) a Clitopilus sp., B. edulis, C. piperatus and I. badia; other mycorrhizal associates are yet to be discovered.
DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted 2-Feb-24):
A full-length nrITS sequence of 596 base pairs (bps) was obtained from this material by Steve Russell (ONT-nanopore sequencing). The RiC score is 21, and Steve says the sequence of a subpar quality.
Ten (10) accessions of RET’s species Amanita “sp-N60” crypt. temp. are at the top of the BLASTn hit list, with a similarity range of 98.5~99.5% to the query sequence. Four of these accessions are associated with a single collection from ME, voucher RET 449-6 (ref. = obs 24776 that has been deleted from MO), meaning that that the organism has 4 distinct copies of ITS that have been fished out and resolved by doing bacterial cloning (now ONT-nanopore can handle this problem that Sanger was helpless against). One of these haplotypes is 99.5% similar to Steve’s sequence, while the list similar one comes in at 98.7%.
Considering that the ITS sequence of “sp-N60” has some inherent intraspecific variability, as demonstrated by the 10 GenBank accessions, and the present sequence has some quality issues, the overall BLASTn profile suggests MO511797 is likely to be “sp-N60”. Still, a single-click distance-based tree built in GenBank from 30+ relevant accessions of taxa selected from the BLASTn hit list, places this collection on a separate branch as a sister taxon to the “sp-N60” lineage.
In early November 2023, Amanita “sp-N60” was deprecated on MO in favor of Amanita russuloides Peck by Herbert Baker. The reason for deprecation was not given, but I surmise this may have something to do with RET’s Facebook forum and the discussions taking place there that I am not part of. However, it’s still a legit name on RET’s website. At the same time, no knew information has transpired about A. russuloides, and it still remains a poorly understood species as per RET’s original remarks in the brief tab at www.amanitaceae.org/?Amanita%20russuloides.

results.notes:
I find A. phalloides growing under a lone European linden tree, Tilia cordata, in my neighborhood, less than 50 yards from my home. It fruits there gregariously every year, almost always in early to mid-November. This year it fruited at the end of October, probably because of the hot and dry summer and cooler weather arriving earlier than usual in the fall. My first record of the Death Cap from this site dates back to 2014, obs 188196. Other mycorrhizal fungi associated with this basswood are the European Phlegmacium flavescentipes (obs 344736 & obs 344743, sequenced), which often fruits concurrently in cold weather with the Death Cap, a brown-capped russula that I saw for the first time this year, also in October (fruiting decimated by squirrels), and a gray-capped grisette that fruited only once during summer time a few years ago following heavy rains (too far gone for preservation).
I also saw the Death Cap growing under other basswood trees elsewhere on the property in summer 2021. It’s possible that all the basswood trees here came from the same nursery.
